  "local_port": 38316,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are the best alternatives to Patreon you'd recommend?",
  "response": "There are several great alternatives to Patreon depending on your needs as a creator or supporter. Here are some of the best options:\n\n### 1. **Ko-fi**  \n   - **Best for:** One-time donations and small projects.  \n   - **Features:** No platform fees for basic services, \"Gold\" membership for recurring payments, and a shop feature for selling digital products or merchandise.  \n   - **Pros:** Easy to use, no upfront costs, and no obligation to post content regularly.  \n\n### 2. **Buy Me a Coffee**  \n   - **Best for:** Simple and lightweight crowdfunding.  \n   - **Features:** One-time donations, memberships, and the ability to offer exclusive content to supporters.  \n   - **Pros:** User-friendly interface, low fees (5% per transaction), and integrates well with social media.  \n\n### 3. **Substack**  \n   - **Best for:** Writers and newsletter creators.  \n   - **Features:** Platform for creating paid newsletters, with subscription-based revenue.  \n   - **Pros:** Focused on long-form content, easy to monetize email subscribers, and no upfront costs.  \n\n### 4. **Gumroad**  \n   - **Best for:** Selling digital products, memberships, and subscriptions.  \n   - **Features:** Flexible pricing, memberships, and the ability to sell physical products alongside digital ones.  \n   - **Pros:** Low fees (10% + payment processor fees), great for creators selling products directly.  \n\n### 5. **Liberapay**  \n   - **Best for:** Open-source projects and recurring donations.  \n   - **Features:** Recurring donations with no platform fees (funded by users).  \n   - **Pros:** Non-profit and transparent, ideal for community-supported projects.  \n\n### 6. **Patreon Alternatives Directories**  \n   - **Tipeee** (for French-speaking creators)  \n   - **Drip** (now merged with Kickstarter)  \n   - **OnlyFans** (for adult content and niche creators)  \n\n### 7. **Membership Platforms**  \n   - **Podia**: For selling memberships, courses, and digital downloads.  \n   - **Thinkific**: Focused on creating and selling online courses.  \n   - **Teachable**: Similar to Thinkific, great for course creators.  \n\n### 8. **Crowdfunding Platforms**  \n   - **Kickstarter**: For project-based funding.  \n   - **Indiegogo**: Similar to Kickstarter but with more flexible funding options.  \n\n### 9. **Social Media Platforms**  \n   - **YouTube Memberships**: For video creators with a large following.  \n   - **Twitch Subscriptions**: For streamers and gamers.  \n\n### 10. **Custom Solutions**  \n   - **Self-hosted Membership Plugins** (e.g., MemberPress, WP Simple Pay) for WordPress users.  \n   - **Stripe**: For creators who want to build their own payment and subscription system.  \n\n### Choosing the Right Platform:  \n- **Consider your content:** Some platforms are better suited for specific types of content (e.g., Substack for newsletters, Gumroad for products).  \n- **Fees:** Compare platform fees and payment processor costs.  \n- **Ease of use:** Look for a platform that integrates easily with your workflow.  \n- **Audience:** Choose a platform that aligns with where your audience is most active.  \n\nEach platform has its strengths, so explore a few to see which fits your needs best!",
  "temperature": 1.0,
